# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acetal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acetal/1-3-5-trioxane] Trioxane can be obtained by the acid-catalyzed cyclic trimerization of formaldehyde in concentrated aqueous solution.
[src:acetal/1-3-5-trioxane] Trioxane can be used interchangeably with formaldehyde and with paraformaldehyde, however the cyclic structure is more stable and it can require high temperatures in order to react.
[src:acetal/1-3-5-trioxane] It is a precursor for the production of polyoxymethylene plastics, of which about one million tons per year are produced.
[src:acetal/1-3-5-trioxane] Other applications exploit its tendency to release formaldehyde.
[src:acetal/1-3-5-trioxane] As such it is used as a binder in textiles, wood products, etc.
[src:acetal/1-3-5-trioxane] Trioxane is combined with hexamine and compressed into solid bars to make hexamine fuel tablets, used by the military and outdoorsmen as a cooking fuel.
[src:acetal/1-3-5-trioxane] In the laboratory, trioxane is used as an anhydrous source of formaldehyde.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The first example of a stable heteroalkene E=C or E=E' (E, E' = P) containing a heavy group 15 element was reported in 1982 by Yoshifuji.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] After the realization of heavier heteroalkenes, the field of organometallic chemistry began exploring the idea of heteroallenes E=C=E' and E=C=C=E', in which one or more carbon atom of an allene is substituted by a heavier atom.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The first of these heteroallenes containing a heavier group 15 element to be reported was synthesized in 1984 by Yoshifuji.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] 1-phosphaallene, also referred to as ethenylidenephosphine or λ3-phosphaallene, was first synthesized using the 2,4,6-tri-t-butylphenyl (supermesityl, or Mes*) moiety as a sterically protecting group.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The most widely known example of 1-phosphaalenes is the Mes* substituted 3H-phosphallene, where a hydrogen is bonded to the terminal carbon atom, which was synthesized by Märkl and Reitinger in 1988.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Some more recent advances made in regards to 1-phosphaallenes include the development of simpler synthetic routes and the discovery of synthetic pathways using phosphaallenes to create molecules that are typically only synthesized through complicated methods.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Multiple synthetic routes to 1-phosphaallenes have been reported.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The most common are Phospha-Wittig-Horner reactions, rearrangement of alkylynlphosphines with a base present, dehydrochlorination of a chlorovinylphospine, and the reaction of lithium with a C,C-dichlorophosphirane.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] More recent synthetic advances include the dehydrobromination of phosphaalkenes the hydroalumination of alkynylphosphines.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The Phospha-Wittig-Horner reaction, first reported by Mathey et al. in 1992, was initially developed as a synthetic route to convert aldehydes and ketones into C-mono and C,C-disubstituted phosphaalkenes, respectively.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] This method was then adapted to rapidly synthesize phosphaallenes by reacting phosphaketenes with an organolithium base, such as lithium diisopropylamide or t-BuOLi.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] n-BuLi is used as a strong base in the synthesis of a phosphaallene.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] A lithium complex can be used to synthesize phosphaallenes.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Like the transition from an alkyne to an allene in organic chemistry, phosphaallenes can be synthesized from alkynylphosphines by adding a strong base such as n-butyllithium (n-BuLi).
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] These complexes are typically useful due to the broad range of stable products that can be obtained from this synthetic route.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Multiple stable phosphaallenes have been synthesized from LiC≡CR and ArP(H)Cl (R = Ph, t-Bu, Me, CH2OSiMe3).
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The basicity of the lithium complex is essential to the success of these reactions.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The dehydrochlorination of 1-chlorovinylphosphine by DBU (1,8-diazabicyclo-[5.4.0]undec-7-ene) yields a variety of results, depending on the structure of the initial chlorovinylphosphine.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Many of these reactions require temperatures between −90 °C and 0 °C to ensure a stable product is formed.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] As many of these reactions are warmed, oligomerization of the phosphaallene occurs.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Other reactions following this synthetic route occur with gas phase reagents at 250 °C.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] In this synthetic route, a dichlorocarbene is first reacted with a phosphaethylene.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The addition of t-BuLi to the resulting 2,2-dichlorophosphirane yields the phosphaallene.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] This route includes an insertion of carbon into the P=C bond of a phosphaalkene.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] (Z)-2,5-dibromo-1-phosphapent-1-ene with the sterically cumbersome Mes* moiety was reacted with t-BuOK to yield the cyclopropylidenephosphaethene product.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Treatment of the (Z)-2,5-dibromo-1-phosphapent-1-ene reagent with a weaker base, EtONa yields a non-cyclic isomer that can undergo cyclization in the presence of t-BuOK.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] In 2019, a new synthetic route for the synthesis of phosphaallenes was reported by Klöcker and coworkers.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The hydroalumination of dialkynylphosphines with different alkylaluminium hydrides resulted in the elimination of dialkylaluminium alkynides and the desired phosphaallenes.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Many of the phosphaallenes Klöcker and coworkers synthesized spontaneously decomposed into less-desired products, but the newly reported synthetic method did allow for the isolation of some highly reactive compounds that had not been isolated previously.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] In 2022, the most notable aspect of 1-phosphaallenes is their reactivity.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes contain three reactive centers: the P=C bond, the C=C bond, and the phosphorus atom.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The P=C bond and the C=C bond are thought to be electronically independent of one another.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] This gives rise to a wide variety of reactivity, which is similar to that of phosphaalkenes.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Without a large steric hindrance, most phosphaallenes quickly dimerize in a [2+2]- or [2+3]-cycloaddition to yield four- or five-membered rings.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Thus, in order to prevent dimerization, a bulky moiety such as Mes* is often used.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Dimerization frequently occurs in a head-to-tail manner, exhibiting coupling between either the two C=C bonds or the two P=C bonds.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The regioselectivity of these dimerization reactions depends on the substituents on the C in the 3 position.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Nucleophilic alkoxide as well as n-BuLi will add to the P=C bond of a phosphaallene.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] As seen in the reaction scheme, the central C atom is the preferred location for proton attack due to the partial negative charge it possesses.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The reaction of phosphaallenes with dichlorocarbenes results in a [2+1]-cycloaddition to the P=C double bond, which results in stable heterocyclic compounds.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes have also been investigated as reagents to form carbenes.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Reacting the phosphaallene H2P=C=PH with acetylene yields a carbene via [3 + 2]-cycloaddition.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Crystal structure showing phosphaallene-transition metal coordination.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes can coordinate in an ɳ1 or ɳ2 fashion depending on the metal and experimental conditions.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Recent studies into the coordination behavior of the 3H-phosphaallene with tungsten (W) show that both stable and unstable phosphaallenes can bond to W through and ɳ1-coordination mode via a P-W bond.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Due to the stabilizing effect of coordination, reacting transient phosphaallenes with W has become a common method to create stable phosphaallenes that can then be characterized.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] These studies have also demonstrated that 3H-phosphaallenes exhibit ɳ2-coordination to Pt via side-on overlap between Pt and the P=C double bond resulting in a three-membered PtPC heterocycle.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Head-to-tail dimerization of 3H-phosphaallene.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Tricyclic phosphine resulting from decomposition via irradiation.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Decomposition of the 3H-phosphaallene occurs at room-temperature to produce several products via P=C (head-to-tail) or C=C dimerization.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] One decomposition pathway results in an unusual tricyclic phosphine which can be selectively formed by irradiating a solution of the phosphaallene, iBu2AlH, and TripP(C≡CtBu)2 in n-hexanes for 60h with a mercury vapor lamp.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Under these conditions, the tricyclic phosphine was isolated in high yield and a purity of >95%.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Recently, two novel 1-benzodihydrophosphetes were synthesized by heating 3H-phosphaallene Mes*P=C=C(H)R (R = tBu, Ad) in toluene at 110 °C for 16-20h.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The resulting 1- benzodihydrophosphetes were not stable unless coordinated to tungsten.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The phosphorus-bound H of the product can be used in catalyst-free hydrophosphination reactions and in the synthesis of bulky phosphine ligands.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Hydroboration is used as a method to reduce unsaturated compounds, and has been used to reduce P-C double or triple bonds in phosphaalkenes and phosphaalkynes.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Hydroboration of the 3H-phosphaallene Mes*-P=C=C(H)-tBu with 1:1 molar ratio of phosphaallene to H3B(SMe2) yielded a di(phosphaalkenyl)borane, and the reaction in 2:1 molar ratio of phosphaallene to H3B(SMe2) yielded the desired product with a B atom bound to two P=C double bonds.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The hydroboration of the C=C bond was preferred over the hydroboration of the P=C bond.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Phosphaallenes are typically colorless or pale yellow in color, and are often crystalline in structure; however, few crystal structures have been reported for this class of compounds.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] One compound, ArP=C=CPh2 (Ar =Mes*) was synthesized and characterized by single crystal X-ray diffraction.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] This compound showed a relatively short P=C double bond length of 1.625(4)Å and a short C=C bond length of 1.1327(5)Å, which closely resembles the bond length in an allene.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The crystal structure also showed a bent geometry with the P=C=C bond angle at 168.0(3)°.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] This bent geometry is thought to be a result of both steric and electronic effects.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] One possible explanation for the observed bent geometry is the bonding model postulated by Lappert et al. which described the bonding between P and the C as singlet states that act in a double π-donor-acceptor fashion.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The crystal structure of another 1-phosphaallene RP=C=CHR' (R= Mes*, R' = tBu) displays the same bent geometry with the P=C=C bond angle being reported as 170.7°.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] Further, this compound also contains a short P=C bond length (1.634Å) and a short C=C bond length (1.136Å).
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The electronic structure of 1-phosphaallene is nearly identical to that of phosphaalkene.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The HOMO in both molecules is the π-orbital of the C=P bond, which is primarily P in character.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The LUMO in both structures, is also heavily localized over the C=P bond.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] However, the dipole moment in phosphaallenes is larger than that of phosphaalkenes.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] In compounds with the antisymmetric form X=C=Y, IR stretching bands are observed in the 1600–2300 cm−1 region.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] However, the IR spectra of 1-phosphaallenes do not contain bands in this region, which suggests that the phosphaallene P=C=C is relatively symmetric.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] In the phosphaallene H2C=C=PH, stretching frequencies are observed at 1788 and 789 cm−1, which are attributed to the C=C bond and the C=P bond, respectively.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] In similar compounds containing a C=C=N skeleton, there is a very strong band present within the 1600 – 2300 cm−1 region.
[src:acetal/1-phosphaallenes] The presence of two stretching frequencies rather than one strong frequency in the phosphaallene supports that the C=C and C=P bonds are nearly independent of one another electronically.
[src:acetal/acetal] In organic chemistry, an **acetal** is a functional group with the connectivity R2C(OR')2.
[src:acetal/acetal] Here, the R groups can be organic fragments (a carbon atom, with arbitrary other atoms attached to that) or hydrogen, while the R' groups must be organic fragments, not hydrogen.
[src:acetal/acetal] The two R' groups can be equivalent to each other (a "symmetric acetal") or not (a "mixed acetal").
[src:acetal/acetal] An acetal is formed from and convertible to two alcohol molecules and an aldehyde or ketone, but acetals have substantially different chemical stability and reactivity as compared to the analogous carbonyl compounds.
[src:acetal/acetal] The central carbon atom has four bonds to it, and is therefore saturated and has tetrahedral geometry.
[src:acetal/acetal] The IUPAC originally deprecated the usage of the word ketal altogether, but has since reversed its decision.
[src:acetal/acetal] However, in contrast to historical usage, ketals are now a subset of acetals, a term that now encompasses both aldehyde- and ketone-derived structures.
[src:acetal/acetal] If one of the R groups has an oxygen as the first atom (that is, there are more than two oxygens single-bonded to the central carbon), the functional group is instead an orthoester.
[src:acetal/acetal] In contrast to variations of R, both R' groups are organic fragments.
[src:acetal/acetal] If one R' is a hydrogen, the functional group is instead a hemiacetal, while if both are H, the functional group is a ketone hydrate or aldehyde hydrate.
[src:acetal/acetal] Formation of an acetal occurs when the hydroxyl group of a hemiacetal becomes protonated and is lost as water.
[src:acetal/acetal] The carbocation that is produced is then rapidly attacked by a molecule of alcohol.
[src:acetal/acetal] Loss of the proton from the attached alcohol gives the acetal.
[src:acetal/acetal] Acetals are stable compared to hemiacetals but their formation is a reversible equilibrium as with esters.
[src:acetal/acetal] As a reaction to create an acetal proceeds, water must be removed from the reaction mixture, for example, with a Dean–Stark apparatus, lest it hydrolyse the product back to the hemiacetal.
[src:acetal/acetal] The formation of acetals reduces the total number of molecules present (carbonyl + 2 alcohol → acetal + water) and therefore is generally not favourable with regard to entropy.
[src:acetal/acetal] One situation where the reaction is not entropically unfavourable is when a single diol molecule is used rather than two separate alcohol molecules (carbonyl + diol → acetal + water).
[src:acetal/acetal] Acetalization and ketalization are the organic reactions that involve the formation of an acetal (or ketals) from aldehydes and ketones, respectively.
[src:acetal/acetal] Since each step is often a rapid equilibrium, the reaction must be driven by removal of water.
[src:acetal/acetal] Methods for removing water include azeotropic distillation and trapping water with desiccants like aluminium oxide and molecular sieves.
[src:acetal/acetal] Steps assumed to be involved: protonation of the carbonyl oxygen, addition of the alcohol to the protonated carbonyl, protonolysis of the resulting hemiacetal or hemiketal, and addition of the second alcohol.
[src:acetal/acetal] Another way to avoid the entropic cost is to perform the synthesis by acetal exchange (**transacetalization**), using a pre-existing acetal-type reagent as the OR'-group donor rather than simple addition of alcohols themselves.
[src:acetal/acetal] One type of reagent used for this method is an orthoester.
[src:acetal/acetal] In this case, water produced along with the acetal product is destroyed when it hydrolyses residual orthoester molecules, and this side reaction also produces more alcohol to be used in the main reaction.
[src:acetal/acetal] Since many sugars are polyhydroxy aldehydes and ketones, sugars are a rich source of acetals and ketals.
[src:acetal/acetal] Most glycosidic bonds in carbohydrates and other polysaccharides are acetal linkages.
[src:acetal/acetal] Cellulose is a ubiquitous example of a polyacetal.
[src:acetal/acetal] Benzylidene acetal and acetonide as protecting groups used in research of modified sugars.
[src:acetal/acetal] Acetals also find application as chiral auxiliaries.
[src:acetal/acetal] Indeed acetals of chiral glycols like, e.g. derivatives of tartaric acid can be asymmetrically opened with high selectivity.
[src:acetal/acetal] This enables the construction of new chiral centers.
[src:acetal/acetal] Formaldehyde forms a rich collection of acetals.
[src:acetal/acetal] This tendency reflects the fact that low molecular weight aldehydes are prone to self-condensation such that the C=O bond is replaced by an acetal.
[src:acetal/acetal] The acetal formed from formaldehyde (two hydrogens attached to the central carbon) is sometimes called a *formal* or the methylenedioxy group.
[src:acetal/acetal] The acetal formed from acetone is sometimes called an acetonide.
[src:acetal/acetal] Formaldehyde forms paraformaldehyde and 1,3,5-trioxane.
[src:acetal/acetal] Polyoxymethylene (POM) plastic, also known as "acetal" or "polyacetal", is a polyacetal (and a polyether), and a polymer of formaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetal] Acetaldehyde converts to paraldehyde and metaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetal] Phenylsulfonylethylidene (PSE) acetal is an example of arylsulfonyl acetal possessing atypical properties, like resistance to acid hydrolysis which leads to selective introduction and removal of the protective group.
[src:acetal/acetal] 1,1-Diethoxyethane (acetaldehyde diethyl acetal), sometimes called simply "acetal", is an important flavouring compound in distilled beverages.
[src:acetal/acetal] Two ketals of ethyl acetoacetate are used in commercial fragrances.
[src:acetal/acetal] Fructone (CH3C(O2C2H4)CH2CO2C2H5), an ethylene glycol ketal, and fraistone (CH3C(O2C2H3CH3)CH2CO2C2H5), a propylene glycol ketal, are commercial fragrances.
[src:acetal/acetal] Used in a more general sense, the term **X**,**Y**-*acetal* also refers to any functional group that consists of a carbon bearing two heteroatoms **X** and **Y**.
[src:acetal/acetal] For example, *N*,*O*-acetal refers to compounds of type R1R2C(OR)(NR'2) (R,R' ≠ H) also known as a *hemiaminal ether* or aminal, a.k.a. aminoacetal.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:acetal/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is miscible with water and serves as an important organic solvent in industry, home, and laboratory.
[src:acetal/acetone] About 6.7 million tonnes were produced worldwide in 2010, mainly for use as a solvent and for production of methyl methacrylate and bisphenol A, which are precursors to widely used plastics.
[src:acetal/acetone] It is a common building block in organic chemistry.
[src:acetal/acetone] It serves as a solvent in household products such as nail polish remover and paint thinner.
[src:acetal/acetone] It has volatile organic compound (VOC)-exempt status in the United States.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is produced and disposed of in the human body through normal metabolic processes.
[src:acetal/acetone] Small quantities of it are present naturally in blood and urine.
[src:acetal/acetone] People with diabetic ketoacidosis produce it in larger amounts.
[src:acetal/acetone] Medical ketogenic diets that increase ketone bodies (acetone, β-hydroxybutyric acid and acetoacetic acid) in the blood are used to suppress epileptic attacks in children with treatment-resistant epilepsy.
[src:acetal/acetone] From the 17th century, and before modern developments in organic chemistry nomenclature, acetone was given many different names.
[src:acetal/acetone] They included "spirit of Saturn", which was given when it was thought to be a compound of lead and, later, "pyro-acetic spirit" and "pyro-acetic ester".
[src:acetal/acetone] Prior to the name "acetone" being coined by French chemists, it was named "mesit" (from the Greek μεσίτης, meaning mediator) by Carl Reichenbach, who also said that methyl alcohol consisted of mesit and ethyl alcohol.
[src:acetal/acetone] Names derived from mesit include mesitylene and mesityl oxide which were first synthesised from acetone.
[src:acetal/acetone] In 1839, the name "acetone" began to be used, because it was obtained from acetic acid.
[src:acetal/acetone] Unlike many compounds with the *acet-* prefix which have a 2-carbon chain, acetone has a 3-carbon chain.
[src:acetal/acetone] That has caused confusion because there can not be a ketone with 2 carbons.
[src:acetal/acetone] The prefix refers to acetone's relation to vinegar (*acetum* in Latin, also the source of the words "acid" and "acetic"), rather than its chemical structure.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone was first produced by Andreas Libavius in 1606 by distillation of lead(II) acetate.
[src:acetal/acetone] In 1832, French chemist Jean-Baptiste Dumas and German chemist Justus von Liebig determined the empirical formula for acetone.
[src:acetal/acetone] In 1833, French chemists Antoine Bussy and Michel Chevreul decided to name acetone by adding the suffix *-one* to the stem of the corresponding acid (viz, acetic acid) just as a similarly prepared product of what was then confused with margaric acid was named margarone.
[src:acetal/acetone] By 1852, Alexander William Williamson, an English chemist, realized that acetone was methyl acetyl; the following year, the French chemist Charles Frédéric Gerhardt concurred.
[src:acetal/acetone] In 1865, a German chemist, August Kekulé published the modern structural formula for acetone.
[src:acetal/acetone] Johann Josef Loschmidt had presented the structure of acetone in 1861, but his privately published booklet received little attention.
[src:acetal/acetone] During World War I, Chaim Weizmann developed the biochemical process for industrial production of acetone (Weizmann Process).
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is produced directly or indirectly from propene.
[src:acetal/acetone] Approximately 83% of acetone is produced via the cumene process; as a result, acetone production is tied to phenol production.
[src:acetal/acetone] Other processes involve the direct oxidation of propylene (Wacker-Hoechst process), or the hydration of propylene to give 2-propanol, which is oxidized (dehydrogenated) to acetone.
[src:acetal/acetone] Previously, acetone was produced by the dry distillation of acetates, for example calcium acetate in ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:acetal/acetone] After that time during World War I, acetone was produced using acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation with *Clostridium acetobutylicum* bacteria, which was developed by Chaim Weizmann (later the first president of Israel) in order to help the British war effort, in the preparation of Cordite.
[src:acetal/acetone] This acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation was eventually abandoned when newer methods with better yields were found.
[src:acetal/acetone] In 2010, the worldwide production capacity for acetone was estimated at 6.7 million tonnes per year.
[src:acetal/acetone] With 1.56 million tonnes per year, the United States had the highest production capacity, followed by Taiwan and China.
[src:acetal/acetone] The largest producer of acetone is INEOS Phenol, owning 17% of the world's capacity, with also significant capacity (7–8%) by Mitsui, Sunoco and Shell in 2010.
[src:acetal/acetone] INEOS Phenol also owns the world's largest production site (420,000 tonnes/annum) in Beveren, Belgium.
[src:acetal/acetone] The spot price of acetone in summer 2011 was 1100–1250 USD/tonne in the United States.
[src:acetal/acetone] Humans exhale several milligrams of acetone per day and it arises from the decarboxylation of acetoacetate.
[src:acetal/acetone] Small amounts of acetone are produced in the body by the decarboxylation of ketone bodies.
[src:acetal/acetone] Certain dietary patterns including prolonged fasting and high-fat low-carbohydrate dieting, can produce ketosis, in which acetone is formed in body tissue.
[src:acetal/acetone] Certain health conditions, such as alcoholism and diabetes, can produce ketoacidosis, uncontrollable ketosis that leads to a sharp, and potentially fatal, increase in the acidity of the blood.
[src:acetal/acetone] Since it is a byproduct of fermentation, acetone is a byproduct of the distillery industry.
[src:acetal/acetone] It is produced by terrestrial vegetation, undefined ocean processes, incomplete combustion of biomass, or oxidation of hydrocarbons in the atmosphere.
[src:acetal/acetone] Like most ketones, acetone exhibits the keto–enol tautomerism in which the nominal keto structure (CH3)2C=O of acetone itself is in equilibrium with the enol isomer (CH3)C(OH)=(CH2) (**prop-1-en-2-ol**).
[src:acetal/acetone] In acetone vapor at ambient temperature, only 2.4×10−7% of the molecules are in the enol form.
[src:acetal/acetone] In the presence of suitable catalysts, two acetone molecules also combine to form the compound diacetone alcohol (CH3)C=O(CH2)C(OH)(CH3)2, which on dehydration gives mesityl oxide (CH3)C=O(CH)=C(CH3)2.
[src:acetal/acetone] This product can further combine with another acetone molecule, with loss of another molecule of water, yielding phorone and other compounds.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is a weak Lewis base that forms adducts with soft acids like I2 and hard acids like phenol.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone also forms complexes with divalent metals.
[src:acetal/acetone] Under ultraviolet light, acetone fluoresces.
[src:acetal/acetone] The flame temperature of pure acetone is 1980 °C.
[src:acetal/acetone] At its melting point (−96 °C) is claimed to polymerize to give a white elastic solid, soluble in acetone, stable for several hours at room temperature.
[src:acetal/acetone] To do so, a vapor of acetone is co-condensed with magnesium as a catalyst onto a very cold surface.
[src:acetal/acetone] The outcome of irradiation of acetone is wavelength dependent.
[src:acetal/acetone] The latter process is relevant to the atmospheric chemistry of acetone.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone can then be metabolized either by CYP2E1 via methylglyoxal to D-lactate and pyruvate, and ultimately glucose/energy, or by a different pathway via propylene glycol to pyruvate, lactate, acetate (usable for energy) and propionaldehyde.
[src:acetal/acetone] About a third of the world's acetone is used as a solvent, and a quarter is consumed as acetone cyanohydrin, a precursor to methyl methacrylate.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is used to synthesize methyl methacrylate.
[src:acetal/acetone] The third major use of acetone (about 20%) is synthesizing bisphenol A.
[src:acetal/acetone] Bisphenol A is a component of many polymers such as polycarbonates, polyurethanes, and epoxy resins.
[src:acetal/acetone] Many millions of kilograms of acetone are consumed in the production of the solvents methyl isobutyl alcohol and methyl isobutyl ketone.
[src:acetal/acetone] These products arise via an initial aldol condensation to give diacetone alcohol.
[src:acetal/acetone] Condensation with acetylene gives 2-methylbut-3-yn-2-ol, precursor to synthetic terpenes and terpenoids.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is a good solvent for many plastics and some synthetic fibers.
[src:acetal/acetone] It is used for thinning polyester resin, cleaning tools used with it, and dissolving two-part epoxies and superglue before they harden.
[src:acetal/acetone] It is used as one of the volatile components of some paints and varnishes.
[src:acetal/acetone] Although itself flammable, acetone is used extensively as a solvent for the safe transportation and storage of acetylene, which cannot be safely pressurized as a pure compound.
[src:acetal/acetone] Vessels containing a porous material are first filled with acetone followed by acetylene, which dissolves into the acetone.
[src:acetal/acetone] One litre of acetone can dissolve around 250 litres of acetylene at a pressure of 10 bars (1.0 MPa).
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is used as a solvent by the pharmaceutical industry and as a denaturant in denatured alcohol.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is also present as an excipient in some pharmaceutical drugs.
[src:acetal/acetone] A variety of organic reactions employ acetone as a polar, aprotic solvent, e.g. the Jones oxidation.
[src:acetal/acetone] Because acetone is cheap, volatile, and dissolves or decomposes with most laboratory chemicals, an acetone rinse is the standard technique to remove solid residues from laboratory glassware before a final wash.
[src:acetal/acetone] Despite common desiccatory use, acetone dries only via bulk displacement and dilution.
[src:acetal/acetone] It forms no azeotropes with water (see azeotrope tables).
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone also removes certain stains from microscope slides.
[src:acetal/acetone] An acetone/dry ice mixture cools many low-temperature reactions.
[src:acetal/acetone] Make-up artists use acetone to remove skin adhesive from the netting of wigs and mustaches by immersing the item in an acetone bath, then removing the softened glue residue with a stiff brush.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is a main ingredient in many nail polish removers because it breaks down nail polish.
[src:acetal/acetone] It is used for all types of nail polish removal, like gel nail polish, dip powder and acrylic nails.
[src:acetal/acetone] The chemical modifies peptides, both at α- or ε-amino groups, and in a poorly understood but rapid modification of certain glycine residues.
[src:acetal/acetone] In pathology, acetone helps find lymph nodes in fatty tissues (such as the mesentery) for tumor staging.
[src:acetal/acetone] The liquid dissolves the fat and hardens the nodes, making them easier to find.
[src:acetal/acetone] Dermatologists use acetone with alcohol for acne treatments to chemically peel dry skin.
[src:acetal/acetone] Common agents used for chemical peeling are salicylic acid, glycolic acid, azelaic acid, 30% salicylic acid in ethanol, and trichloroacetic acid (TCA).
[src:acetal/acetone] Prior to chemexfoliation, the skin is cleaned and excess fat removed in a process called defatting, using acetone, hexachlorophene, or a combination of these agents.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone has been shown to have anticonvulsant effects in animal models of epilepsy, in the absence of toxicity, when administered in millimolar concentrations.
[src:acetal/acetone] It has been hypothesized that the high-fat low-carbohydrate ketogenic diet used clinically to control drug-resistant epilepsy in children works by elevating acetone in the brain.
[src:acetal/acetone] Because of their higher energy requirements, children have higher acetone production than most adults – and the younger the child, the higher the expected production.
[src:acetal/acetone] This indicates that children are not uniquely susceptible to acetone exposure.
[src:acetal/acetone] External exposures are small compared to the exposures associated with the ketogenic diet.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone has a relatively long lifetime in the atmosphere of about 2 weeks.
[src:acetal/acetone] Because of its long lifetime, it can be transported by atmospheric winds to the upper troposphere and lower stratosphere where it can influence hydrogen radical (HOx) production and ozone (O3) levels.
[src:acetal/acetone] These two peroxy radicals can then undergo a series of reactions to produce hydrogen oxide radicals (HOx) and can therefore have a significant impact on atmospheric chemistry including concentration of ozone (O3) in the upper troposphere.
[src:acetal/acetone] Photolysis is just one possible processes that removes acetone from the atmosphere.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone can also be removed by ocean processes and by deposition to dry land surfaces.
[src:acetal/acetone] The contributions of each sink to the removal of acetone from the atmosphere is still not fully understood.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone's most hazardous property is its extreme flammability.
[src:acetal/acetone] In small amounts, acetone burns with a dull blue flame; in larger amounts, fuel evaporation causes incomplete combustion and a bright yellow flame.
[src:acetal/acetone] When above acetone's flash point of −20 °C (−4 °F), air mixtures of 2.5‑12.8% acetone (by volume) may explode or cause a flash fire.
[src:acetal/acetone] Vapors can flow along surfaces to distant ignition sources and flash back.
[src:acetal/acetone] Static discharge may ignite acetone vapors, though acetone has a very high ignition initiation energy and accidental ignition is rare.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone's auto-ignition temperature is relatively high 465 °C (869 °F); moreover, auto-ignition temperature depends upon experimental conditions, such as exposure time, and has been quoted as high as 535 °C.
[src:acetal/acetone] Even pouring or spraying acetone over red-glowing coal will not ignite it, due to the high vapour concentration and the cooling effect of evaporation.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone should be stored away from strong oxidizers, such as concentrated nitric and sulfuric acid mixtures.
[src:acetal/acetone] It may explode when stored with chloroform in the presence of a base.
[src:acetal/acetone] When oxidized without combustion, for example with hydrogen peroxide, acetone may form acetone peroxide, a highly unstable primary explosive.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone peroxide may be formed accidentally, e.g. when waste peroxide is poured into waste solvents.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone occurs naturally as part of certain metabolic processes in the human body, and has been studied extensively and is believed to exhibit only slight toxicity in normal use.
[src:acetal/acetone] There is no strong evidence of chronic health effects if basic precautions are followed.
[src:acetal/acetone] It is generally recognized to have low acute and chronic toxicity if ingested and/or inhaled.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is not regarded as a carcinogen, a mutagen, or a concern for chronic neurotoxicity effects.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone can be found as an ingredient in a variety of consumer products ranging from cosmetics to processed and unprocessed foods.
[src:acetal/acetone] The United States Food and Drug Administration rates acetone as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance when present in food and drink at concentrations from 5 to 8 mg/L.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acetone is an irritant, causing mild skin and moderate-to-severe eye irritation.
[src:acetal/acetone] Like many other solvents, acetone may depress the central nervous system at high vapor concentrations.
[src:acetal/acetone] Acute toxicity for mice by ingestion (LD50) is 3 g/kg, and by inhalation (LC50) is 44 g/m3 over 4 hours.
[src:acetal/acetone] In 1995, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) removed acetone from the list of volatile organic compounds.
[src:acetal/acetone] In making its decision EPA conducted an extensive review of the available toxicity data on acetone, which was continued through the 2000s.
[src:acetal/acetone] It found that the evaluable "data are inadequate for an assessment of the human carcinogenic potential of acetone".
[src:acetal/acetonide] In organic chemistry, an **acetonide** is the functional group composed of the cyclic ketal of a diol with acetone.
[src:acetal/acetonide] The more systematic name for this structure is an isopropylidene ketal.
[src:acetal/acetonide] Acetonide is a common protecting group for 1,2- and 1,3-diols.
[src:acetal/acetonide] The protecting group can be removed by hydrolysis of the ketal using dilute aqueous acid.
[src:acetal/acetonide] The acetonides of small di- and triols, as well as many sugars and sugar alcohols, are common.
[src:acetal/acetonide] An example of its use as a protecting group in a complex organic synthesis is the Nicolaou Taxol total synthesis.
[src:acetal/acetonide] It is a common protecting group for sugars and sugar alcohols, a simple example being solketal.
[src:acetal/acetonide] The acetonides of corticosteroid are used in dermatology, because their increased lipophilicity leads to better penetration into the skin.
[src:acetal/acetoxy-group] In organic chemistry, the **acetoxy group** (abbr.
[src:acetal/acetoxy-group] **AcO–** or **–OAc**; IUPAC name: **acetyloxy**), is a functional group with the formula −OCOCH3 and the structure −O−C(=O)−CH3.
[src:acetal/acetoxy-group] As the *-oxy* suffix implies, it differs from the acetyl group (−C(=O)−CH3) by the presence of an additional oxygen atom.
[src:acetal/acetoxy-group] The name acetoxy is the short form of *acetyl-oxy*.
[src:acetal/acetoxy-group] An acetoxy group may be used as a protection for an alcohol functionality in a synthetic route although the protecting group itself is called an acetyl group.
[src:acetal/acetoxy-group] An alcohol is not a particularly strong nucleophile and, when present, more powerful nucleophiles like amines will react with the above-mentioned reagents in preference to the alcohol.
[src:acetal/acetyl] In organic chemistry, an **acetyl group** is a functional group denoted by the chemical formula −COCH3 and the structure −C(=O)−CH3.
[src:acetal/acetyl] It is sometimes represented by the symbol **Ac** (not to be confused with the element actinium).
[src:acetal/acetyl] In IUPAC nomenclature, an acetyl group is called an **ethanoyl** **group**.
[src:acetal/acetyl] An acetyl group contains a methyl group (−CH3) that is single-bonded to a carbonyl (C=O), making it an acyl group.
[src:acetal/acetyl] The acetyl moiety is a component of many organic compounds, including acetic acid, the neurotransmitter acetylcholine, acetyl-CoA, acetylcysteine, acetaminophen (also known as paracetamol), and acetylsalicylic acid (also known as aspirin).
[src:acetal/acetyl] Acetylation is the chemical reaction known as "ethanoylation" in the IUPAC nomenclature.
[src:acetal/acetyl] It depicts a reactionary process that injects an acetyl functional group into a chemical compound.
[src:acetal/acetyl] The opposite reaction is called "**de**acetylation", and this is the **removal** of the acetyl group.
[src:acetal/acetyl] Enzymes which perform acetylation on proteins or other biomolecules are known as acetyltransferases.
[src:acetal/acetyl] In biological organisms, acetyl groups are commonly transferred from acetyl-CoA to other organic molecules.
[src:acetal/acetyl] Acetyl-CoA is an intermediate in the biological synthesis and in the breakdown of many organic molecules.
[src:acetal/acetyl] Acetyl-CoA is also created during the second stage of cellular respiration (pyruvate decarboxylation) by the action of pyruvate dehydrogenase on pyruvic acid.
[src:acetal/acetyl] Proteins are often modified via acetylation, for various purposes.
[src:acetal/acetyl] For example, acetylation of histones by histone acetyltransferases (HATs) results in an expansion of local chromatin structure, allowing transcription to occur by enabling RNA polymerase to access DNA.
[src:acetal/acetyl] However, removal of the acetyl group by histone deacetylases (HDACs) condenses the local chromatin structure, thereby preventing transcription.
[src:acetal/acetyl] Acetylation can be achieved by chemists using a variety of methods, most commonly with the use of acetic anhydride or acetyl chloride, often in the presence of a tertiary or aromatic amine base.
[src:acetal/acetyl] The amine base is primarily used to capture free protons, but may also further activate the acetyl group towards nucleophilic attack.
[src:acetal/acetyl] Acetylated organic molecules exhibit increased ability to cross the selectively permeable blood–brain barrier.
[src:acetal/acetyl] Acetylation helps a given drug reach the brain more quickly, making the drug's effects more intense and increasing the effectiveness of a given dose.
[src:acetal/acetyl] The acetyl group in acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin) enhances its effectiveness relative to the natural anti-inflammatant salicylic acid.
[src:acetal/acetyl] In similar manner, acetylation converts the natural painkiller morphine into the far more potent heroin (diacetylmorphine).
[src:acetal/acetyl] There is some evidence that acetyl-L-carnitine may be more effective for some applications than L-carnitine.
[src:acetal/acetyl] Acetylation of resveratrol holds promise as one of the first anti-radiation medicines for human populations.
[src:acetal/acetyl] The term "acetyl" was coined by the German chemist Justus von Liebig in 1839 to describe what is now known as the vinyl group (coined in 1851).
[src:acetal/acetyl] "Acetyl" is derived from the Latin *acētum,* meaning "vinegar.", and the Greek *Húlē,* meaning substance, or material.
